$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}f'(x)
\\\\
&=\dfrac{d}{dx}(\cos(x)x^{-2})
\\\\
&=\dfrac{d}{dx}(\cos(x))x^{-2}+\cos(x)\dfrac{d}{dx}(x^{-2})&&\gray{\text{The product rule}}
\\\\
&=-\sin(x)x^{-2}+\cos(x)(-2)x^{-3}&&\gray{\text{Differentiate }\cos(x)\text{ and }x^{-2}}
\\\\
&=-\sin(x)x^{-2}-2\cos(x)x^{-3}&&\gray{\text{Simplify}}
